Absa Group Ltd | Europe
Self-help underway stay Overweight
WHAT'S CHANGEDAbsa Group Ltd (ABGJ.J)FromPrice TargetZac 19,600

Current price levels discount undemanding earnings expectations while increased focus on returns, energized leadership and steady progress towards improving the quality of underlying franchises suggest value as improvements slowly emerge. Stay Ow, Target price revised to R220 (previously R196)

We maintain FY25e dHEPS estimates, raising FY26/27e by \(\sim 3\% /2\%\) with a 3- year CAGR of \(9\%\) . ROE target of \(16\%\) for FY26e, seen as a stretch for now; although increased focus on returns brings slow and steady improvement. Key leadership appointments and the strategy refresh expected in 2H25 offer catalysts ABG trades at \(0.9x\) fwd PB and a \(17\%\) discount to peers for a comparable earnings outlook, with a \(26\%\) total return upside to our R220 TP, making it attractive.

Following 1H25 results we leave FY25e dHEPS estimates unchanged, while increasing FY26/27e \(\sim +3\% / + 2\%\) respectively, leaving our 3yr dHEPS CAGR only narrowly below consensus (MSe: \(+9\%\) , Cons: \(+10\%\) ). We now see dHEPS growth for FY25e/FY26e/FY27e at \(+10\% / + 10\% / + 8\%\) respectively. Modest NII downgrades for NIM pressure are offset by upgrades to NIR for CIB momentum while we leave opex unchanged, so we now see PPOP higher by \(+1\% / + 2\%\) for FY25e/26e at \(\pm 3\% / + 7\%\) . We raise credit losses by \(+3\% / + 1\%\) for FY25e/26e as asset quality improvement tempo lags our initial expectations, taking CLR to \(0.94\% /0.87\%\) for FY25e/26e, but tracking FY25 guidance for 'top end of 75- 100bps TTC range'.

We note an improved focus on returns and see ROE progressing slowly from current levels, yet see the \(16\%\) ROE target as a stretch, for now. While we are encouraged by the momentum in CIB (via loan volumes and trading income) and welcome progress in PBB's client primacy and digitization journey (rewards program clients \(+40\%\) , app downloads \(+33\%\) , digitally active clients up to \(38\%\) ), work still remains to improve efficiency and productivity levels to bring CIR to the c51- 52% (currently \(53.2\%\) ) required to durably lift the group ROE. That said we see

management's shift towards a client- led, returns- focused Pan African model to better leverage portfolio diversification benefits and improve efficiencies as a step in the right direction. We also like the greater focus on group capital, elimination of capital subsidies with more reflective capital charges cascading down to client and business unit level, which should improve return outcomes in time. We see ROE trending \(14.8\% /15.2\% /15.3\%\) for FY25e/FY26e/FY27e, suggesting further upside should management deliver on their \(16\%\) FY26 target ROE.

Potential Catalysts: 1) Appointing a reputable head of SA retail banking, announcement expected within c2 months. 2) Presenting a sound, refreshed strategy later in 2H25. 3) Delivering benefits from improved integration/ harmonization. 4) Continuing to meet guidance and delivering cost saving targets.

Potential Risks. 1) Asset quality pressures, in business banking and consumer segments that remain under pressure. 2) Sovereign risk pressures potentially increase, particularly in Mozambique ( \(\sim 1.3\%\) of assets, \(\sim 2.4\%\) of earnings) and in Botswana. ( \(\sim 1.7\%\) of assets, \(\sim 3.5\%\) of earnings). 3) Return of leadership instability. 4) Competitive pressure undermines client momentum.

levels. This change reflects a c30bps decrease to our Cost of Equity to reflect the improved South Africa risk free rate implied via the yield on South African 10yr government bonds since our last update and the earnings upgrades described above.

We upgrade our bull case TP to R253 (previously R229, +10%), implying 34% upside to current levels. This change reflects NIR upgrades through stronger trading income, improve client primacy and stronger loan growth in Africa as well as the unwind in time value of money since our last update. We upgrade our bear case TP to R134 (previously R119, +13%), implying 29% downside to current levels. This change reflects a partial unwind of more bearish expectations on NIR and loan growth given 1H25's progress on primacy/digitization as well increased focus on product level returns and leadership changes. The time value of money unwind also impacts TP changes.

With management citing sovereign risk pressures building around Mozambique and to a lesser extent Botswana in its 1H25 commentary on the operating environment, we contextualize Absa's high- level group exposure to these markets as follows:

Mozambique contributes \(\sim 1.3\%\) of assets, \(\sim 0.6\%\) of loans, \(\sim 2.3\%\) of revenues and \(\sim 2.4\%\) of earnings Botswana contributes \(\sim 1.7\%\) of assets, \(\sim 1.8\%\) of loans, \(\sim 1.9\%\) of revenues and \(\sim 3.5\%\) of earnings

We also quantify the sensitivity of the group income statement to a range of hypothetical adverse fair value impacts on the holdings of government paper in each of the respective subsidiaries below. This shows that for a c10- 20% adverse fair value movement on the in- country securities portfolio, the adverse impact on ABG's FY25e group earnings would be c2- 4% for both Botswana and Mozambique. This however assumes that a fair value shock would apply across instrument tenors, which in practice may be relatively less for shorter dated tenors, which banks typically hold.

ARO grows faster than SA, while SA recovers off a depressed earnings base. CLR averages \(0.86\%\) to FY27e, cost growth matches revenue growth. \(12\%\) dHEPS CAGR FY24- 27e with FY27e RoE at \(16.0\%\)

Normalising credit losses drive earnings. NIM hedges ease rate cutting pressure on NIM. Modest NIR \((6\%\) CAGR to FY26e). Moderate loan growth \((7\%\) CAGR to FY27e) and CLR prints \(0.94\% /0.87\% /0.87\%\) for FY25e/26e/27e relative to 75- 100bps TTC range. \(- 9\%\) dHEPS CAGR FY24- 27e, with FY27e RoE at \(15.3\%\) . However, slightly softer in the short run at \(14.8\%\) for FY25e.

Low SA growth (GDP averages \(0.6\%\) pa) contains loan growth \((- 5\%\) CAGR to FY27e) and NIR momentum \((- 5\%\) CAGR to FY27e), which combines with sticky cost growth \((6\%\) CAGR to FY27e) to see little efficiency gains.
